 his Leavitt descent from Sarah Hooker","link_text":"Henrietta Swan Leavitt"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Leavitt","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Leavitt","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM868"},"career":[{"role":"Member","organization":"Massachusetts legislature"},{"role":"President","organization":"Franklin County Anti-Slavery Society","start_year":1840}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"social_reform","header":"The Liberty Party’s man for Lieutenant Governor","body":"President of the Franklin County Anti-Slavery Society, he accepted the new Massachusetts Liberty Party’s 1840 nomination for Lieutenant Governor — the abolitionist ticket his son Joshua’s party-building made possible. His household sheltered Basil Dorsey alongside his sons’."}],"slug":"roger-leavitt-1771"},"HD0867":{"id":"HD0867","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00685","mother_id":"X00252"},"tags":["abolitionist","minister","newspaper","newspaper_editor","publisher","underground_railroad","yale_connection","yale_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","entry":"685 (father Roger Leavitt)"}],"birth":{"year":1794,"month":9,"day":8,"city":"Heath","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1873,"month":1,"day":16,"city":"Brooklyn","state":"New York"},"prominent_name_reason":"Joshua Leavitt (1794-1873) — abolitionist editor and publisher. Editor of The Emancipator (abolitionist newspaper) and founding editor of The Independent (influential religious newspaper, New York). Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joshua_Leavitt Son of Roger Hooker Leavitt (H00685), grandson of Sarah Hooker (H00302). First graduated Yale, then became a lawyer, then entered ministry. \"Gained his greatest renown as editor of the Emancipator.\" Helped his brothers operate Underground Railroad stations.","cross_connections":[{"type":"unknown_connection","related_id":"HD1533","display_label":"Joshua Leavitt co-founded the American Geographical Society (INST014) in 1851.","link_text":"Henry Evelyn Pierrepont"},{"type":"legal_adversary_ally","related_id":"X02013","display_label":"Both central figures in the Amistad case — Leavitt organizing the legal defense, Willcox as the federal marshal who held the captives and ultimately announced their freedom.","link_text":"Norris Willcox"},{"related_id":"H01837","display_label":"Amistad defender from another Hooker branch — hosted Mende captives","type":"family_connection","link_text":"Jennette Cowles Williams"},{"related_id":"HD0624","display_label":"Springfield Republican editor inheriting Bowles family abolitionist editorial legacy","type":"family_connection","link_text":"Richard Hooker"},{"type":"amistad_connection","related_id":"X01985","display_label":"sheltered the Mende his committee defended","link_text":"Austin Franklin Williams"},{"type":"artifact","related_id":"X01920","display_label":"also sat for Mathew Brady’s camera","link_text":"Doctor Benjamin Silliman Jr."}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Congregational minister","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joshua_Leavitt","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"social_reform","header":"He formed the Amistad defense committee","body":"On September 4, 1839, Leavitt, Lewis Tappan, and Simeon Jocelyn formed the committee that raised the funds to defend the Amistad captives. His Christian Lyre of 1830 had already made him a publishing force — the first American tunebook in modern hymnal form."},{"header":"Editor of The Emancipator from 1836","detail":"Son of Roger Leavitt of Heath MA; Yale 1814; Yale Divinity 1825. He was a Congregational minister before turning to reform journalism. As editor of The Emancipator (New York, 1837-1848) he published evidence of slavery's brutality while also covering the Amistad case. He helped found the American Anti-Slavery Society with William Lloyd Garrison and served as a delegate to the World Anti-Slavery Convention in London (1840). He was also a leader in the Liberty Party and wrote extensively on the economics of slavery (The Financial Power of Slavery, 1840). His brother Roger Hooker Leavitt ran an Underground Railroad station in Montague MA. His unknowing cousin was Henry Evelyn Pierrepont (HD1533) — they co-founded the American Geographical Society in 1851 without apparently knowing they were both descendants of Thomas Hooker. (DAB; Yale; Wikipedia on Joshua Leavitt)","body":"He edited The Emancipator — the flagship US abolitionist newspaper — from 1836 onward. Co-founded the New York Anti-Slavery Society in 1833 and broke from William Lloyd Garrison in 1840 to form the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society with Lewis Tappan.","number":2,"category":"character"},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Sheltered an escaped slave for over five years","body":"In 1836 he directed escaped slave Basil Dorsey to his brother Roger Hooker Leavitt's Underground Railroad station at Charlemont MA. Dorsey later lived with the Leavitt family in New York City for more than five years — a major personal commitment of household resources to the antislavery cause."},{"number":4,"category":"politics","header":"Architect of the Liberty Party, 1844","body":"He was the prime architect of the Liberty Party and ran James G. Birney for president in 1844 — contemporaries called him 'Father of the Liberty Party.' His 1840 tract 'Financial Power of Slavery' was the most-circulated piece of his political career."},{"number":5,"category":"education","header":"Co-founded American Geographical Society, 1851","body":"He co-founded the American Geographical Society in 1851 with Henry Evelyn Pierrepont. Both were 6th-generation descendants of Thomas Hooker through entirely separate branches — neither known to have been aware of their shared ancestry."}],"marriages":[],"education":[{"notes":"Per Pocumtuck Valley Memorial Association history.","school_name":"Yale","institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Rev. Joshua Leavitt","title":"Reverend","first_name":"Joshua","last_name":"Leavitt","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781295541/Joshua_Leavitt_by_Mathew_B_Brady___Studio_circa_1860_hnfuy2.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST014"},{"institution_id":"INST015"},{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1814"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM582"},"slug":"joshua-leavitt-1794"},"HD0868":{"id":"HD0868","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00685","mother_id":"X00252"},"tags":["underground_railroad","abolitionist"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1805,"month":7,"day":21,"city":"Heath","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1885,"month":7,"day":17,"city":"Waterloo","state":"Iowa"},"marriages":[{"children_ids":["HD0870"],"spouse_id":"X01344","marriage_number":1},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"X03311","date_year":1839,"children_ids":[]},{"marriage_number":3,"spouse_id":"X03312","date_year":1877,"children_ids":[]},{"marriage_number":4,"spouse_id":"X03313","date_year":1882,"children_ids":[]}],"prominent_name_reason":"Col. Roger Hooker Leavitt — Underground Railroad operator. His home in Charlemont MA is on the National Park Service's National Underground Railroad Network to Freedom. Sheltered fugitive slave Basil Dorsey (escaped Frederick County MD 1836) for over five years. Colonel in the Massachusetts militia. Member of Massachusetts legislature. Advocate for the Hoosac Tunnel. Died in Waterloo, Iowa visiting son John Hooker Leavitt, 1885. Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Hooker_Leavitt Family correspondence at Library of Congress Manuscript Division.","gender":"male","number_of_marriages":4,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Underground Railroad conductor; Massachusetts senator","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Hooker_Leavitt","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Roger Hooker Leavitt","notes":"Named \"Hooker\" honoring maternal Hooker ancestry through grandmother Sarah Hooker (H00302).","first_name":"Roger","last_name":"Leavitt","middle_name":"Hooker","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781293573/28545170_1497140793_i5iubz.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM868"},"education":[{"school_name":"Hopkins Academy, Hadley","type":"secondary"},{"school_name":"Dartmouth College","type":"undergraduate","notes":"briefly"}],"career":[{"role":"Senator","organization":"Massachusetts Senate"},{"role":"President","organization":"Franklin County Anti-Slavery Society","start_year":1836},{"role":"Incorporator","organization":"Troy & Greenfield Railroad","start_year":1848}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"social_reform","header":"Basil Dorsey lived five years in hiding","body":"The fugitive Basil Dorsey, escaped from Maryland in 1836, sheltered more than five years among the Leavitt households at Charlemont — hidden in plain sight while the 1840 census recorded no persons of color there. Brother Joshua wrote from New York: “do all that Christian benevolence requires in his care.”"},{"number":2,"category":"social_reform","header":"The Utica mob converted his parents","body":"Violence by pro-slavery factions at the October 1835 Utica convention — which he attended with brothers Joshua and Hart — fully converted the elder Leavitts to the cause. Within a year he was president of the Franklin County Anti-Slavery Society."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Four wives, the last at seventy-six","body":"Widowed of Keziah Osgood Hunt in 1838, he married her sister Eliza the next year; Olive Warriner in Chicago at seventy-one; and at seventy-six, the schoolteacher Lucy Trowbridge — her first marriage, at fifty-one. He was also among the earliest promoters of the Hoosac Tunnel."}],"slug":"roger-leavitt-1805"},"X01344":{"id":"X01344","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0868","children_ids":["HD0870"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1807,"month":4,"day":17,"city":"Heath","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1838,"month":11,"day":11,"city":"Charlemont","state":"Massachusetts"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Keziah Osgood Hunt","first_name":"Keziah","middle_name":"Osgood","maiden_name":"Hunt","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781293928/28545375_c9ffafc3-25a6-4fb6-9319-238c71c66f03_ocftks.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM868"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Dead at thirty-one, three sons left","body":"She died in November 1838 — the same year Basil Dorsey’s wife died under the family’s protection — leaving John Hooker, William Hunt, and Henry Jenkins, the eldest just seven."}],"slug":"keziah-hunt-1807"},"X03311":{"id":"X03311","bio":{"display_name":"Eliza Hunt Leavitt","gender":"female"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":false,"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1802,"month":1,"day":18,"city":"Heath","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1876,"month":6,"day":1},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0868","date_year":1839,"children_ids":[]}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM868"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"She married her sister’s widower","body":"A year after Keziah’s death, Eliza married Roger Hooker and raised her sister’s three boys; she had no children of her own."}],"slug":"eliza-hunt-leavitt-x03311"},"X03312":{"id":"X03312","bio":{"display_name":"Olive Wood Longley Warriner Leavitt","gender":"female"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":false,"number_of_marriages":2,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1824,"month":5,"day":16,"city":"Hawley","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1880,"month":12,"day":2,"city":"Charlemont","state":"Massachusetts"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id"